Does flouride gas being produced by refinement have to go into a container to be used to produce UF4/TF4 or can it be used for direct processing?

43 minutes ago, Maelstrom Vortex said:

Does flouride gas being produced by refinement have to go into a container to be used to produce UF4/TF4 or can it be used for direct processing?

I think it needs to be in liquid form, and for that you have to have TWO containers--one for the gas, and one for the liquid. Note that the one for the liquid needs to be one of the ISRU cryostat containers that has a flourine-liquid flourine slider so that it can convert the gas into the liquid, either that or you need a refrigerator module. You get faster conversion of gas to liquid with a refrigerator module, and those have integrated tanks, but you'll still need one to store the liquid. It also may be worthwhile to have a pressurized gas tank (the big balloon looking things, with or without shrouds) as a buffer to keep production from shutting down to overflow or products being lost because you enabled overflow if anything goes haywire.

Correction

There's also a backwards sign change somewhere in the math for the Alcubierre drives; I was just orbiting Kerbin and I matched speeds with a ship orbiting nearby in the same direction, setting my relative speed indicator to target and SAS to retrograde until the speed difference read zero, but when I exited warp at the halfway mark to check and make sure the speeds were matched, I was somehow orbiting Kerbol in the flat wrong direction. There's no way I managed to reverse a solar orbit by 20,000 m/s with 5,000m/s velocity change relative to Kerbin, so I think somewhere in your math you've got a +/- sign reversal.

I use the graphene radiators, especially scaled-down 'wing edge' radiators and the curved graphene ones. Those are good for spaceplanes, you might want something different for stations. The titanium inline radiator is good in atmosphere, where graphene doesn't work well; the wraparound cools better, but causes immense drag (as you can tell just by looking at it) so a spaceplane cooled by the wraparounds is unlikely to reach orbit.

Hi, me again. I was wondering if there was a way to harvest nitrogen or make it in one of the ISRUs. It appears to e the best propellant in terms of ISP.

Use an ISRU refrigerator (hex or in-line) or all-in-one. Have a nitrogen storage tank ready, if you're making liquid nitrogen make sure the nitrogen slider on your refrigerator is all the way to liquid. Have some air intakes on your ship. Make sure you're using a KSPI reactor because this all takes megawatts of energy, which is more than any stock part can generate. Use the right-click menu on your refrigerator and click for the control window. Select 'atmospheric extraction'. The atmosphere on Kerbin, like Earth, is mostly nitrogen, which means you can harvest large amounts quickly... and then use it to give your suborbital spaceplane that last boost it needs.
